  <DISS_content>
    <DISS_abstract>
      <DISS_para>In my dissertation, I explore the world of Iranian theatre from 1997 to the present, focusing on the work of its directors and their productions of canonical Western plays. I specifically interrogate the ways Iranian theatre artists may be speaking politically to audiences while evading censorship. I argue that Iranian directors imbue their productions with an aesthetics of ambiguity, encouraging appellative readings of their work through an apperceptive lens. In my analysis of several important productions by Vahid Rahbani, Manijeh Mohamedi, Zahra Sabri, Homayoun Ghanizadeh, and others, I illustrate the risks of such political work, as well as the innovative styles of performance that this counter-censorial strategy encourages. Ultimately, I demonstrate that the relationship between Iranian theatre artists and the state is incredibly complex, and it is not necessarily always destructive. In fact, I show how working through and around censorship has enhanced these director&#8217; abilities at creating theatrical worlds, and as a result they are now internationally-recognized theatremakers.</DISS_para>
    </DISS_abstract>
